I was out today at the outskirts of Ipoh City where there are many ex-mining pools (wetlands-like habitat) and limestone hills. I observed a Changeable Hawk-Eagle (Nisaetus cirrhatus) hunting for prey – it attempted to catch Grey Herons (Ardea cinerea). It landed in a ‘concealed’ section of an Albizia saman (Rain Tree) which housed a heronry. This heronry on the Albizia saman tree has 25-30 adult birds with 10-12 active nests, in various stages.
When the Changeable Hawk-Eagle approached and landed in the tree, all the adult Grey Herons gave out loud, continual distress calls. The adult Grey Herons had their crest raised, wings outspread and continued to make loud vocalisation. Over the next 30 minutes the Changeable Hawk-Eagle made four attempts to catch a Grey Heron. Twice it swooped down to the nesting birds but the nesting adults put up a fierce defence. Two other times it went after a flying adult Grey Heron but they managed to evade it. An audio recording of the vocal distress of the Grey Herons can be heard here.

rmk:
Grey Herons in a heronry. The recording follows XC669636. I counted 22 nests with at least 10 occupied. The nests are spread along this linear woodland covering around 100m from end to end. 

I could see one young one had already hatched and in fact looked fairly large. There were at least two making the incessant begging calls that are heard throughout. The adults often left the nests with a loud honk call (e.g. 16:10) but also made other calls such as the guttural sound at the beginning when arriving at the nest. I guess this was as they bring back food but I did not visually confirm this. 

Recorded with home made SASS and Olympus LS-12. EQ adjusted below 150 Hz to remove a little background rumble and below 600 Hz in a few places to remove light vehicle noise.
